03911nam a22005415i 9780226202693DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262026937 a10.7208/97802262026932doi  a(DE-B1597)524951  a(OCoLC)659576508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN6328.L3bE43 2010 7aTRU0000002bisacsh04a0822221 aElder, Robert K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLast Words of the Executed /cRobert K. Elder. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Noose -- t2. The Firing Squad -- t3. The Electric Chair -- t4. The Gas Chamber -- t5. Lethal Injection -- tA Note on Accuracy and Sources -- tTimeline of Capital Punishment in the United States -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSome beg for forgiveness. Others claim innocence. At least three cheer for their favorite football teams. Death waits for us all, but only those sentenced to death know the day and the hour—and only they can be sure that their last words will be recorded for posterity. Last Words of the Executed presents an oral history of American capital punishment, as heard from the gallows, the chair, and the gurney. The product of seven years of extensive research by journalist Robert K. Elder, the book explores the cultural value of these final statements and asks what we can learn from them. We hear from both the famous—such as Nathan Hale, Joe Hill, Ted Bundy, and John Brown—and the forgotten, and their words give us unprecedented glimpses into their lives, their crimes, and the world they inhabited. Organized by era and method of execution, these final statements range from heartfelt to horrific. Some are calls for peace or cries against injustice; others are accepting, confessional, or consoling; still others are venomous, rage-fueled diatribes. Even the chills evoked by some of these last words are brought on in part by the shared humanity we can’t ignore, their reminder that we all come to the same end, regardless of how we arrive there. Last Words of the Executed is not a political book. Rather, Elder simply asks readers to listen closely to these voices that echo history. The result is a riveting, moving testament from the darkest corners of society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCapital punishmentxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aCapital punishmentzUnited States. 0aLast words. 7aTRUE CRIME / General.2bisacsh1 aTerkel, Studs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTerkel, Studs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226202693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226202693.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles